The distinction is mostly about whether you’re asking me to produce pixels or to build a mental model.

* Create image → I generate a new image. This uses the image generation system to actually produce artwork, illustrations, renders, diagrams, etc.
    * “Create an Apex Legends character.”
    * “Draw a castle on Mars.”
    * “Edit this photo to look like watercolor.”
* Visualize → By itself, this often means “imagine it” or “help me mentally picture it.” I might respond with a vivid description, a conceptual explanation, or an internal reconstruction. If your intent is clearly “make me an image,” I’ll usually generate one anyway.

For example:

“Visualize a medieval library.”

I might describe towering shelves, stained-glass windows, and candlelight. If you instead said:

“Create an image of a medieval library.”

I’ll generate the actual picture.

In practice, there’s a lot of overlap because people often use “visualize” to mean “show me.” When your intent is clearly to see something, I generally treat visualize, draw, render, illustrate, make an image, and create an image as requests to generate an image.

So:

* Visualize = can be internal (description/mental model) or external (image), depending on context.
* Create image = explicitly produce an image.